Data Description

The data include customer demographic information (age, income, etc.), the customer's relationship with the bank (mortgage, securities account, etc.), and the customer response to the last personal loan campaign (Personal Loan).

Attribute Information

 ID : Customer ID

 Age : Customer's age in completed years

 Experience : years of professional experience

 Income : Annual income of the customer (in $)

 ZIP Code : Home Address ZIP code

 Family : Family size of the customer

 CCAvg : Avg. spending on credit cards per month (in $)

 Education : Education Level

  1. Undergrad
  2. Graduate
  3. Advanced/Professional  Mortgage : Value of house mortgage if any (in $)

 Personal Loan : Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?

 Securities Account : Does the customer have a securities account with the bank?

 CD Account : Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank?

 Online : Does the customer use internet banking facilities?

 Credit card : Does the customer use a credit card issued by Bank? </font>

Objective

The classification goal is to predict the likelihood of a liability customer buying personal loans.

Comments:¶

- The columns experience and Age are highly correlated to each other and the value is almost near to 1. It means a perfect collinearity exists between these two independent variables, which is very rare in practice. Thus while calculating any one of these two independent variables can be dropped off.¶

- This is dropping of any one column can help to make the model simpler and avoid overfitting of the model. By which, we can get almost same accuracy in both training and testing sets.¶

- By using the Principle of Parsimony, the model can be made simpler (Occam's Razor) while capturing the collective effort of other independent variables on target variable¶

# creating odd list of k for KNN
mylist = list(range(1,20))

# substituating just the odd ones
neighbors = list(filter(lambda x: x % 2 != 0, mylist))

Run the KNN with no of neighbours ranging from 1,3,5..19 and¶

Find the optimal number of neighbours from the above list using the Misclassification error¶

In [442]:
# creating an empty list to hold accuracy scores
ac_scores = []

# performing accuracy metrics for values from 1,3,5,7,.....19
for k in neighbors:
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = k)
    knn.fit(x_train,y_train)
    # predict the response
    y_predKNN = knn.predict(x_test)
    # evaluate accuracy
    scores = accuracy_score(y_test, y_predKNN)
    ac_scores.append(scores)
    
# Changing to misclassification error
MSE = [1- x for x in ac_scores]

# determining best k
optimal_k = neighbors[MSE.index(min(MSE))]
print("the optimal number of neigbors is %d" % optimal_k)

the optimal number of neigbors is 9

6. Comments On the Best Model and basis of selecting the model as Best one

1. This data frame has a target variable which is categorical in nature (0 or 1 / No or Yes), thus this is a classification task, hence, logistic regression, KNN and Naïve Bayes, SVM, Decision Tree models can be used to draw the inference and to predict the likelihood of a customer buying personal loan offered to them. NB: The SVM model and KNN model algorithm are uesd to give class output however, Logistic Regression, Random Forest model algorithm are used to give Probability output.¶

2. Here we have tried to predict the category of customers by building three models such as logistic regression, KNN and Naïve Bayes.¶

3. These three models such as Logistic regression, Naïve Bayes and KNN gave an accuracy of 94.27%, 87.47% and 91.00% respectively on testing sets. The accuracy is the fraction of times, my models prediction turned out to be right. Thus from this comparison, the model built through Logistic Regression is a clear winner since it is able to predict the customer’s category with a very high accuracy.¶

4. However, we cannot take decision by relying upon only one measure, because, lot of other deciding factors are there to decide which model is the best to predict correctly the likelihood of a customer buying personal loans.¶

5. Thus now comparing the precision value among these three models, the precisions is nothing but the measure of accuracy of positives classified by the model or it refers to the percentage of results which are relevant. The precision of these three models such as Logistic regression, Naïve Bayes and KNN are 85.00 %, 41.00% and 58.00% respectively on testing sets. Hence the clear winner in this comparison is Logistic Regression model.¶

6. Again comparing the recall / Sensitivity / True Positive Rate value among these three models, the recall is nothing but the proportion of observed positives that were predicted to be positives or it refers to the percentage of total relevant results correctly classified by the algorithm. The recall of these three models such as Logistic regression, Naïve Bayes and KNN are 51.00 %, 56.00% and 34.00% respectively on testing sets. Hence the clear winner in this comparison is Naïve Bayes model.¶

7. It is to be noted that, both precision and recall values should be very high.¶

8. Thus, from the above three comparison, it is quit hard to take a decision which model gives the best result to predict the likelihood of a customer buying personal loans. Hence we shall calculate the harmonic mean of both Precision and Recall to take the final decision. F1 Score is another measure which is used in binary logistic regression that combines both precision and recall and it is the harmonic mean of recall and precision. Hence the F1 score for Logistic regression, Naïve Bayes and KNN are 64.00 %, 47.00% and 43.00% respectively on testing sets. Thus it can be concluded that the Best model is Logistic Regression model which is able to predict maximum correct likelihood of a customer who will buy a loan.¶

9. Due to very high accuracy value and F1 score, the Logistic regression model is the best model to be chosen to predict the likelihood of a customer buying a personal loan. Hence, it is advisable to opt for Logistic regression model for production.¶

10. Since our target is to minimize the FN value or type II error to give more profit to bank, therefore it is clearly not advisable to go for KNN model rather Logistic Regression model or Naive Bayes model can be of choice model, preferably the Logistic Regression due to its comparative high value of Accuracy and F1 score.¶

11.Here a huge multi collinearity has been observed between the column Age and Experience. Consequently, this multi collinearity may weaken the statistical power of regression model and affects the precision of model adversely, thus to avoid this and to enhance the precision value any one of the said columns can be omitted while building of model. While doing so it is necessary to check the swing of target column due to inclusion or exclusion of these highly collinear attributes.¶

vif['VIF'] = [variance_inflation_factor(x_train1.values,i) for i in range(x_train1.shape[1]) ]
vif['VIF'] = round(vif['VIF'],2)
vif = vif.sort_values(by = 'VIF', ascending = False)

Assumption:

a) A VIF value of 1 indicates there is no relationship / correlation between independent variables and any others.

b) A VIF value between 1 to 5 shows a moderate correlation but not severe enough to warrant corrective measures.

c) A VIF value greater than 5 shows critical levels of multicollinearity and the p value to be checked for.

Thus, Here, we will remove the one by one which are having VIF>5 and p > 0.05

8. Comments after use of VIF and minmax scalar

Accuracy value of Logistic = 0.94¶

Accuracy value of Naïve Baye’s = 0.88¶

Accuracy value of KNN = 0.95¶

f1 - score of Logistic = 0.68¶

f1 - score of Naïve Baye’s = 0.53¶

f1 - score of KNN = 0.71¶

1.Thus, in terms of accuracy, 0.95 >0.94 >0.88, i.e. KNN Accuracy > Logistic Accuracy > Naïve Baye’s Accuracy¶

2. In terms of f1-score, 0.71 >0.68 >0.53, i.e. KKN f1-score > Logistic f1-score > Naïve Baye’s f1-score¶

3. Hence, from the above comparison, it can be clearly understood that, the KNN model is the best model to predict the likelihood of a liability customer buying personal loan.¶
